04749nam a22007095i 9780691188690DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911886907 a10.1515/97806911886902doi  a(DE-B1597)501632  a(OCoLC)1076473203  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJK1764b.H48 2005eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.9732231 aHetherington, Marc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy Trust Matters :bDeclining Political Trust and the Demise of American Liberalism /cMarc Hetherington. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER ONE. Why Political Trust Matters -- tCHAPTER TWO. Political Trust and Its Evolution -- tCHAPTER THREE. Political Distrust, Not Conservatism -- tCHAPTER FOUR. The Dynamic Importance of Political Trust -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Political Trust and Public Support for Government Spending -- tCHAPTER SIX. Political Trust and the Racial Policy Preferences of Whites -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Political Trust and the Demise of Health Care Reform -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Political Trust and the Future of American Politics -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican public policy has become demonstrably more conservative since the 1960s. Neither Jimmy Carter nor Bill Clinton was much like either John F. Kennedy or Lyndon Johnson. The American public, however, has not become more conservative. Why, then, the right turn in public policy? Using both individual and aggregate level survey data, Marc Hetherington shows that the rapid decline in Americans' political trust since the 1960s is critical to explaining this puzzle. As people lost faith in the federal government, the delivery system for most progressive policies, they supported progressive ideas much less. The 9/11 attacks increased such trust as public attention focused on security, but the effect was temporary. Specifically, Hetherington shows that, as political trust declined, so too did support for redistributive programs, such as welfare and food stamps, and race-targeted programs. While the presence of race in a policy area tends to make political trust important for whites, trust affects policy preferences in other, non-race-related policy areas as well. In the mid-1990s the public was easily swayed against comprehensive health care reform because those who felt they could afford coverage worried that a large new federal bureaucracy would make things worse for them. In demonstrating a strong link between public opinion and policy outcomes, this engagingly written book represents a substantial contribution to the study of public opinion and voting behavior, policy, and American politics generally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical alienationzUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aVotingzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188690zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691188690423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188690.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11